# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frequency-synthesizer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] A basic Direct Digital Synthesizer consists of a frequency reference (often a crystal or SAW oscillator), a numerically controlled oscillator (NCO) and a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) as shown in Figure 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The reference oscillator provides a stable time base for the system and determines the frequency accuracy of the DDS.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] It provides the clock to the *NCO*, which produces at its output a discrete-time, quantized version of the desired output waveform (often a sinusoid) whose period is controlled by the digital word contained in the *Frequency Control Register*.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The sampled, digital waveform is converted to an analog waveform by the *DAC*.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The output reconstruction filter rejects the spectral replicas produced by the zero-order hold inherent in the analog conversion process.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] A DDS has many advantages over its analog counterpart, the phase-locked loop (PLL), including much better frequency agility, improved phase noise, and precise control of the output phase across frequency switching transitions.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] Disadvantages include spurious responses mainly due to truncation effects in the NCO, crossing spurs resulting from high order (>1) Nyquist images, and a higher noise floor at large frequency offsets due mainly to the digital-to-analog converter.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] Because a DDS is a sampled system, in addition to the desired waveform at output frequency Fout, Nyquist images are also generated (the primary image is at Fclk − Fout, where Fclk is the reference clock frequency).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] In order to reject these undesired images, a DDS is generally used in conjunction with an analog reconstruction lowpass filter as shown in Figure 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The output frequency of a DDS is determined by the value stored in the frequency control register (FCR) (see Fig.1), which in turn controls the NCO's phase accumulator step size.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] Because the NCO operates in the discrete-time domain, it changes frequency instantaneously at the clock edge coincident with a change in the value stored in the FCR.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The DDS output frequency settling time is determined mainly by the phase response of the reconstruction filter.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] An ideal reconstruction filter with a linear phase response (meaning the output is simply a delayed version of the input signal) would allow instantaneous frequency response at its output because a linear system can not create frequencies not present at its input.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] The superior close-in phase noise performance of a DDS stems from the fact that it is a feed-forward system.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] In a traditional phase locked loop (PLL), the frequency divider in the feedback path acts to multiply the phase noise of the reference oscillator and, within the PLL loop bandwidth, impresses this excess noise onto the VCO output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] A DDS, on the other hand, reduces the reference clock phase noise by the ratio $f_{clk}/f_{o}$ because the fractional division of the clock derives its output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] Reference clock jitter translates directly to the output, but this jitter is a smaller percentage of the output period (by the ratio above).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] Since the maximum output frequency is limited to $f_{clk}/2$ , the output phase noise at close-in offsets is always at least 6 dB below the reference clock phase noise.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/direct-digital-synthesis] At offsets far removed from the carrier, the phase-noise floor of a DDS is determined by the power sum of the DAC quantization noise floor and the reference clock phase noise floor.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] In electronics, a **frequency multiplier** is an electronic circuit that generates an output signal which has a frequency that is a harmonic (multiple) of its input frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Frequency multipliers consist of a nonlinear circuit that distorts the input signal and consequently generates harmonics of the input signal.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A subsequent bandpass filter selects the desired harmonic frequency and removes the unwanted fundamental and other harmonics from the output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Frequency multipliers are often used in frequency synthesizers and communications circuits.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] It can be more economical to develop a lower frequency signal with lower power and less expensive devices, and then use a frequency multiplier chain to generate an output frequency in the microwave or millimeter wave range.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Some modulation schemes, such as frequency modulation, survive the nonlinear distortion without ill effect (but schemes such as amplitude modulation do not).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Frequency multiplication is also used in nonlinear optics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The nonlinear distortion in crystals can be used to generate harmonics of laser light.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] If the sine wave is applied to a linear circuit, such as a non–distortion amplifier, the output is still a sine wave (but may acquire a phase shift).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] However, if the sine wave is applied to a nonlinear circuit, the resulting distortion creates harmonics; frequency components at integer multiples *nf* of the fundamental frequency *f*.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The distorted signal can be described by a Fourier series in *f*.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The nonzero *ck* represent the generated harmonics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] So a frequency multiplier can be built from a nonlinear electronic component which generates a series of harmonics, followed by a bandpass filter which passes one of the harmonics to the output and blocks the others.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] From a conversion efficiency standpoint, the nonlinear circuit should maximize the coefficient for the desired harmonic and minimize the others.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Consequently, the transcribing function is often specially chosen.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Easy choices are to use an even function to generate even harmonics or an odd function for odd harmonics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A full wave rectifier, for example, is good for making a doubler.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] To produce a times-3 multiplier, the original signal may be input to an amplifier that is over driven to produce nearly a square wave.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This signal is high in 3rd order harmonics and can be filtered to produce the desired x3 outcome.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] YIG multipliers often want to select an arbitrary harmonic, so they use a stateful distortion circuit that converts the input sine wave into an approximate impulse train.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The ideal (but impractical) impulse train generates an infinite number of (weak) harmonics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] In practice, an impulse train generated by a monostable circuit will have many usable harmonics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] YIG multipliers using step recovery diodes may, for example, take an input frequency of 1 to 2 GHz and produce outputs up to 18 GHz.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Sometimes the frequency multiplier circuit will adjust the width of the impulses to improve conversion efficiency for a specific harmonic.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Efficiently generating power becomes more important at high power levels.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Linear Class A amplifiers are at best 25 percent efficient.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Push-pull Class B amplifiers are at best 50 percent efficient.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The basic problem is the amplifying element is dissipating power.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Switching Class C amplifiers are nonlinear, but they can be better than 50 percent efficient because an ideal switch does not dissipate any power.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A clever design can use the nonlinear Class C amplifier for both gain and as a frequency multiplier.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Generating a large number of useful harmonics requires a fast nonlinear device, such as a step recovery diode.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Microwave generators may use a step recovery diode impulse generator followed by a tunable YIG filter.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The YIG filter has a yttrium iron garnet sphere that is tuned with a magnetic field.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The step recovery diode impulse generator is driven at a subharmonic of the desired output frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] An electromagnet then tunes the YIG filter to select the desired harmonic.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Frequency multipliers have much in common with frequency mixers, and some of the same nonlinear devices are used for both: transistors operated in Class C and diodes.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] In transmitting circuits many of the amplifying devices (vacuum tubes or transistors) operate nonlinearly and create harmonics, so an amplifier stage can be made a multiplier by tuning the tuned circuit at the output to a multiple of the input frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Usually the power (gain) produced by the nonlinear device drops off rapidly at the higher harmonics, so most frequency multipliers just double or triple the frequency, and multiplication by higher factors is accomplished by cascading doubler and tripler stages.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Frequency multipliers use circuits tuned to a harmonic of the input frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Non-linear elements such as diodes may be added to enhance the production of harmonic frequencies.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Since the power in the harmonics declines rapidly, usually a frequency multiplier is tuned to only a small multiple (twice, three times, or five times) of the input frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Usually amplifiers are inserted in a chain of frequency multipliers to ensure adequate signal level at the final frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Since the tuned circuits have a limited bandwidth, if the base frequency is changed significantly (more than one percent or so), the multiplier stages may have to be adjusted; this can take significant time if there are many stages.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] An electric-field driven micromechanical cantilever resonator is one of the most fundamental and widely studied structures in MEMS, which can provide a high Q and narrow bandpass filtering function.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The inherent square-law nonlinearity of the voltage-to-force transfer function of a cantilever resonator's capacitive transducer can be employed for the realization of frequency doubling effect.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Due to the low-loss attribute (or equivalently, a high Q) offered by MEMS devices, improved circuit performance can be expected from a micromechanical frequency doubler than semiconductor devices utilized for the same task.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Graphene based FETs have also been employed for frequency doubling with more than 90% converting efficiency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] In fact, all ambipolar transistors can be used for designing frequency multiplier circuits.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Graphene can work over a large frequency range due to its unique characteristics.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A phase-locked loop (PLL) uses a reference frequency to generate a multiple of that frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO) is initially tuned roughly to the range of the desired frequency multiple.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The signal from the VCO is divided down using frequency dividers by the multiplication factor.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The divided signal and the reference frequency are fed into a phase comparator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The output of the phase comparator is a voltage that is proportional to the phase difference.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] After passing through a low pass filter and being converted to the proper voltage range, this voltage is fed to the VCO to adjust the frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This adjustment increases the frequency as the phase of the VCO's signal lags that of the reference signal and decreases the frequency as the lag decreases (or lead increases).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] The VCO will stabilize at the desired frequency multiple.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This type of PLL is a type of frequency synthesizer.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] In some PLLs the reference frequency may also be divided by an integer multiple before being input to the phase comparator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This allows the synthesis of frequencies that are N/M times the reference frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This can be accomplished in a different manner by periodically changing the integer value of an integer-N frequency divider, effectively resulting in a multiplier with both whole number and fractional component.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Such a multiplier is called a fractional-N synthesizer after its fractional component.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] Fractional-N synthesizers provide an effective means of achieving fine frequency resolution with lower values of N, allowing loop architectures with tens of thousands of times less phase noise than alternative designs with lower reference frequencies and higher integer N values.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] They also allow a faster settling time because of their higher reference frequencies, allowing wider closed and open loop bandwidths.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] A delta sigma synthesizer adds a randomization to programmable-N frequency divider of the fractional-N synthesizer.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/fractional-n-synthesizer] This is done to shrink sidebands created by periodic changes of an integer-N frequency divider.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A **frequency synthesizer** is an electronic circuit that generates a range of frequencies from a single reference frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Frequency synthesizers are used in devices such as radio receivers, televisions, mobile telephones, radiotelephones, walkie-talkies, CB radios, cable television converter boxes, satellite receivers, and GPS systems.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A frequency synthesizer may use the techniques of frequency multiplication, frequency division, direct digital synthesis, frequency mixing, and phase-locked loops to generate its frequencies.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The stability and accuracy of the frequency synthesizer's output are related to the stability and accuracy of its reference frequency input.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Consequently, synthesizers use stable and accurate reference frequencies, such as those provided by a crystal oscillator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Three types of synthesizer can be distinguished.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The first and second type are routinely found as stand-alone architecture: direct analog synthesis (also called a mix-filter-divide architecture as found in the 1960s e.g., HP 5100A and the more modern direct digital synthesizer (DDS) (table lookup).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The third type are routinely used as communication system IC building blocks: indirect digital (PLL) synthesizers, including integer-N and fractional-N.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The recently emerged TAF-DPS is also a direct approach.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] It directly constructs the waveform of each pulse in the clock pulse train.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A digiphase synthesizer is in some ways similar to a DDS, but it has architectural differences.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] One of its advantages is to allow a much finer resolution than other types of synthesizers with a given reference frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Time-Average-Frequency Direct Period Synthesis (TAF-DPS) focuses on frequency generation for clock signals driving integrated circuits.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Different from all other techniques, it uses a novel concept of time average frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Its aim is to address the two long-standing problems in the field of on-chip clock signal generation: arbitrary frequency generation and instantaneous frequency switching.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Starting from a base time unit, TAF-DPS first creates two types of cycles TA and TB.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] These two types of cycles are then used in an interleaved fashion to produce the clock pulse train.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] As a result, TAF-DPS can address the problems of arbitrary-frequency generation and instantaneous-frequency switching effectively.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The first circuit technology utilizing the TAF concept was the flying-adder or flying-adder PLL, which was developed in late 1990s.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Prior to widespread use of synthesizers, in order to pick up stations on different frequencies, radio and television superheterodyne receivers relied on manual tuning of a local oscillator, which used a resonant circuit to produce the frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The receiver was adjusted to different frequencies by either a variable capacitor or a switch that chose the proper tuned circuit for the desired channel, such as with the turret tuner commonly used in television receivers prior to the 1980s.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] However, the resonant frequency of a tuned circuit is not very stable; variations in temperature and aging of components caused frequency drift and the receiver drifted off the station frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Automatic frequency control (AFC) solves some of the drift problem, but manual retuning was often necessary.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Since transmitter frequencies are stabilized, an accurate source of fixed, stable frequencies in the receiver is desirable.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Quartz crystal resonators are many orders of magnitude more stable than LC circuits and, when used to control the frequency of the local oscillator, offer adequate stability to keep a receiver in tune.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] However, the resonant frequency of a crystal is determined by its dimensions and cannot be varied to tune the receiver to different frequencies.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] One solution is to employ many crystals, one for each frequency desired, and switch the correct one into the circuit.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This technique is practical when only a handful of frequencies are required but quickly becomes costly and impractical in many applications.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] For example, the FM radio band in many countries supports 100 individual channel frequencies from about 88 to 108 MHz; the ability to tune in each channel would require 100 crystals.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Cable television can support even more channels over a much wider band.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A large number of crystals increases cost and requires additional space.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The solution to this was the development of circuits that could generate multiple frequencies from a reference frequency produced by a crystal oscillator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The new synthesized frequencies have the same frequency stability of the master crystal oscillator since they are derived from it.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Coherent techniques generate frequencies derived from a single, stable master oscillator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] In most applications, a crystal oscillator is common, but other resonators and frequency sources can be used.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Incoherent techniques derive frequencies from a set of several stable oscillators.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The vast majority of synthesizers in commercial applications use coherent techniques due to simplicity and low cost.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Multiple techniques are available for coherently synthesizing frequencies including frequency divider, phase locked loop (PLL) and direct digital synthesis (DDS).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The choice of approach depends on several factors, such as cost, complexity, frequency step size, switching rate, phase noise, and spurious output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Many types of frequency synthesizer are available as integrated circuits, reducing cost and size.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Influential early books on frequency synthesis techniques include those by Floyd M.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Gardner (his 1966 *Phaselock Techniques*) and by Venceslav F.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Kroupa (his 1973 *Frequency Synthesis*).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A well-thought-out *design procedure* is considered to be the first significant step to a successful synthesizer project.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] In the system design of a frequency synthesizer, states Manassewitsch, there are as many *best* design procedures as there are experienced synthesizer designers.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] System analysis of a frequency synthesizer involves output frequency range, frequency adjustment increments, frequency stability, phase noise performance, switching time, size, power consumption, and cost.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Crawford says that these are mutually contradictive requirements.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Mathematical techniques analogous to mechanical gear-ratio relationships can be employed in frequency synthesis when the frequency synthesis factor is a ratio of integers.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This method allows for effective planning of distribution and suppression of spectral spurs.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Variable-frequency synthesizers, including DDS, are routinely designed using modular arithmetic arithmetic to represent phase.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A phase-locked loop is a feedback control system.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] It compares the phases of two input signals and produces an error signal that is proportional to the difference between their phases.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The error signal is then low-pass filtered and used to drive a voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO), which creates an output frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The output frequency is fed through a frequency divider back to the input of the system, producing a negative feedback loop.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] If the output frequency drifts, the phase error signal will increase, driving the frequency in the opposite direction so as to reduce the error.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Thus, the output is *locked* to the frequency at the other input.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This other input is called the *reference* and is usually derived from a stable crystal oscillator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The key to the ability of a frequency synthesizer to generate multiple frequencies is the divider placed between the output and the feedback input.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This is usually in the form of a digital counter, with the output signal acting as a clock signal.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The counter is preset to some initial count value, and counts down at each cycle of the clock signal.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] When it reaches zero, the counter output changes state and the count value is reloaded.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This circuit is straightforward to implement using flip-flops, and because it is digital in nature, is very easy to interface to other digital components or a microprocessor.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This allows the frequency output by the synthesizer to be easily controlled and used by a digital system.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Suppose the reference signal is 100 kHz, and the divider can be preset to any value between 1 and 100.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The error signal produced by the comparator will only be zero when the output of the divider is also 100 kHz.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] For this to be the case, the VCO must run at a frequency which is 100 kHz times the divider count value.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Thus it will produce an output of 100 kHz for a count of 1, 200 kHz for a count of 2, 1 MHz for a count of 10 and so on.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Note that only whole multiples of the reference frequency can be obtained with the simplest integer N dividers.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Fractional N dividers which overcome this limitation are readily available.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] In practice, a PLL-based frequency synthesizer cannot operate over a very wide range of frequencies, because the comparator will have a limited bandwidth and may suffer from aliasing problems.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This would lead to false locking situations or an inability to lock at all.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] In addition, it is hard to make a high-frequency VCO that operates over a very wide range.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Many radio applications require frequencies that are higher than can be directly input to the digital counter.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] A fast initial division stage called a *prescaler* can be used to reduce the frequency to a manageable level.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Since the prescaler is part of the overall division ratio, a fixed prescaler can cause problems designing a system that supports the narrow channel spacings typically encountered in radio applications.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This can be overcome using a dual-modulus prescaler.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Further practical aspects include time required to switch between frequencies, time to lock when first switched on, and the level of noise in the output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] All of these are a function of the *loop filter* of the system, which is a low-pass filter placed between the output of the frequency comparator and the input of the VCO.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Usually, the output of a frequency comparator is in the form of short error pulses, but the input of the VCO must be a smooth, noise-free DC voltage.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Heavy filtering will make the VCO slow to respond to changes, causing drift and slow response time, but light filtering can produce noise and instability.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Thus, the design of the filter is critical to the performance of the system and is the main area of focus when designing a synthesizer system.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Many PLL frequency synthesizers can also produce frequency modulation (FM).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The modulating signal is added to the output of the loop filter, directly varying the frequency of the VCO and the synthesizer output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] The modulation will also appear at the phase comparator output, reduced in amplitude by any frequency division.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Any spectral components in the modulating signal too low to be blocked by the loop filter end up back at the VCO input with opposite polarity to the modulating signal, thus cancelling them out.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] (The loop effectively sees these components as VCO noise to be removed.) Modulation components above the loop filter cutoff frequency cannot return to the VCO input, so they remain in the VCO output.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] This simple scheme, therefore, cannot directly handle low-frequency or DC modulating signals, but this is not a problem in the many AC-coupled video and audio FM transmitters that use this method.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] PLL frequency synthesizers can be modulated at low frequency and DC by using two-point modulation to overcome the above limitation.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/frequency-synthesizer] Modulation is applied to the VCO as before, but now is also applied digitally to the synthesizer in sympathy with the analog FM signal using a fast delta sigma ADC.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] A **numerically controlled oscillator** (**NCO**) is a digital signal generator which creates a synchronous (i.e., clocked), discrete-time, discrete-valued representation of a waveform, usually sinusoidal.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] NCOs are often used in conjunction with a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) at the output to create a direct digital synthesizer (DDS).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Numerically controlled oscillators offer several advantages over other types of oscillators in terms of agility, accuracy, stability and reliability.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] NCOs are used in many communications systems including digital up/down converters used in 3G wireless and software radio systems, digital phase-locked loops, radar systems, drivers for optical or acoustic transmissions, and multilevel FSK/PSK modulators/demodulators.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] When clocked, the phase accumulator (PA) outputs a sequence of samples from a modulo-2N sawtooth waveform, which are converted by the phase-to-amplitude converter (PAC) to sinusoid samples, where N is the number of bits carried in the phase accumulator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] N sets the NCO frequency resolution and is normally much larger than the address width of the PAC look-up table.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] For a PAC address width of M, the PA output word must be truncated to M bits as shown in Figure 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] However, the truncated bits can be used for interpolation.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Truncation of the phase output word does not affect frequency accuracy, but it does produce a time-varying, periodic phase error, which is a primary source of spurious products.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Spurious products also result from the finite word length of the PAC output (amplitude) word.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The frequency accuracy relative to the clock frequency is limited only by the precision of the arithmetic used to compute the phase.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] NCOs are phase- and frequency-agile, and can be trivially modified to produce a phase-modulated or frequency-modulated output by summation at the appropriate node, or provide quadrature outputs as shown in the figure.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] A binary phase accumulator consists of an N-bit binary adder and a register configured as shown in Figure 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Each clock cycle produces a new N-bit output consisting of the previous output obtained from the register summed with the frequency control word (FCW) which is constant for a given output frequency.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The resulting output waveform is a staircase with step size $\Delta F$ , the integer value of the FCW.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] In some configurations the phase output is taken from the output of the register, which introduces a one clock cycle latency but allows the adder to operate at a higher clock rate.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The adder is designed to overflow when the sum of the absolute value of its operands exceeds its capacity (2N−1).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The overflow bit is discarded so the output word width is always equal to its input word width.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The remainder $\phi _{n}$ , called the residual, is stored in the register and the cycle repeats, starting this time from $\phi _{n}$ (see figure 2).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Since a phase accumulator is a finite-state machine, eventually the residual at some sample K must return to the initial value $\phi _{0}$ .
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] where GCD is the greatest common divisor function.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The GRR represents the true periodicity for a given $\Delta F$ which for a high resolution NCO can be very long.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Equation (1) shows that the phase accumulator can be thought of as a programmable non-integer frequency divider of divide ratio $\Delta F/2^{N}$ .
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The phase-amplitude converter creates the sample-domain waveform from the truncated phase output word received from the PA.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The PAC can be a simple read only memory containing 2M contiguous samples of the desired output waveform which typically is a sinusoid.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Often, though, various tricks are employed to reduce the amount of memory required.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] This include various trigonometric expansions, trigonometric approximations and methods which take advantage of the quadrature symmetry exhibited by sinusoids.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Alternatively, the PAC may consist of random access memory which can be filled as desired to create an arbitrary waveform generator.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Spurious products are the result of harmonic or non-harmonic distortion in the creation of the output waveform due to non-linear numerical effects in the signal processing chain.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] For other distortion mechanisms created in the digital-to-analog converter, see the corresponding section in the direct-digital synthesizer article.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The number of phase accumulator bits of an NCO (N) is usually between 16 and 64.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] If the PA output word were used directly to index the PAC look-up table, an untenably high storage capacity in the ROM would be required.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] As such, the PA output word must be truncated to span a reasonable memory space.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Truncation of the phase word causes phase modulation of the output sinusoid, which introduces non-harmonic distortion in proportion to the number of bits truncated.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] where W is the number of bits truncated.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] where P is the size of the phase-to-amplitude converter's lookup table in bits, i.e., M in Figure 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Another related spurious generation method is the slight modulation due to the GRR outlined above.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The amplitude of these spurs is low for large N and their frequency is generally too low to be detectable but they may cause issues for some applications.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] One way to reduce the truncation in the address lookup is to have several smaller lookup tables in parallel and use the upper bits to index into the tables and the lower bits to weigh them for linear or quadratic interpolation.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] I.e., use a 24-bit phase accumulator to look up into two 16-bit LUTS.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Address into the truncated 16 MSBs, and that plus 1.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Linearly interpolate using the 8 LSBs as weights.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] (One could instead use 3 LUTs instead and quadratically interpolate).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] This can result in decreased distortion for the same amount of memory at the cost of some multipliers.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Another source of spurious products is the amplitude quantization of the sampled waveform contained in the PAC look-up table(s).
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] If the number of DAC bits is P, the AM spur level is approximately equal to −6.02 P − 1.76 dBc.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Phase truncation spurs can be reduced substantially by the introduction of white gaussian noise prior to truncation.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] The so-called dither noise is summed into the lower W+1 bits of the PA output word to linearize the truncation operation.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Often, the improvement can be achieved without penalty because the DAC noise floor tends to dominate system performance.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Amplitude truncation spurs can not be mitigated in this fashion.
[src:frequency-synthesizer/numerically-controlled-oscillator] Introduction of noise into the static values held in the PAC ROMs would not eliminate the cyclicality of the truncation error terms and thus would not achieve the desired effect.
